Rather than starting over with a new stringstream and appending it to uuidStr on each iteration of the loop, I think it'd be a bit more direct and efficient to have a single stringstream and call `.str()` on it once after the loop terminates, e.g. something like:

```
stringstream tmp;
for (...)
{
  tmp << stuff << ...;
}
string uuidStr = tmp.str();
```

One other little tidy-up while taking care of the formatting issues -- the formatting directives (hex, setfill, setw) don't need to be re-applied on every iteration, so this would be cleaner as just:

```
tmp << hex << setfill('0') << setw(2);
for (...)
{
  tmp << uuidReorder[i];
}
```

(Also, I'd suggest simplifying `sizeof(uint8_t) * 2` to just `2`.)

Ah yes, I see now that std::setw() gets reset after you use it (once), even though the others (hex, setfill) remain in effect.  Ugh, what a mess of a stdlib I/O mechanism...anyway, with that in mind it could at least be trimmed down to:

```
std::stringstream tmp;
tmp << std::hex << std::setfill('0');
for (...)
{
    tmp << std::setw(2) << (uint16_t)bytes[i];
}
```

